IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: Narrative: On May 11th, 2023, the Frederick County Department of Social Services received a complaint regarding concerns that Olivia Stergiou (DOB 01/19/1980) had left her 1 year old, Isaiah Antony Young (DOB 12/11/2021), and her 12 year old children unattended in the family home (8151 Rocky Ridge Road, Thurmont, MD) overnight on Friday, May 5th, through Saturday, May 6th. A relative was made aware early morning on May 6th and picked up the children. This relative contacted Stergiou, who refused to return home to care for her children. This relative filed for and was granted emergency custody of the 12 year old. Isaiah, however, was returned to Stergious care. Stergiou left the family home with Isaiah on May 12th, 2023. Stergiou did not take any personal belongings for either herself or Isaiah. Stergiou and Isaiah were unable to be located by Child Protective Services to ensure the well-being of Isaiah. On June 1st, 2023 at approximately 1209 hours, I received communication from CPS Social Worker McGuire requesting assistance in locating Isaiah and Stergiou. SW McGuire expressed concerns that Stergiou is unable to meet the childs basic needs. SW McGuire detailed attempts at meeting with Stergiou. SW McGuire advised that Stergiou had cut communication with her several times, not shown for scheduled meetings, and refused to provide any indication of Isaiahs health and well-being. Isaiahs pediatrician expressed concerns that Isaiah had unmet medical needs, and had recently shown signs of malnourishment. His pediatrician and SW McGuire both expressed concerns that if he were not quickly located, that there was a potential for there to be lasting, permanent consequences for his health and well-being. SW McGuire provided a phone number of 202-910-3381 for Stergiou as well as information regarding a rental vehicle she was believed to be driving: a black Kia Sorento displaying Florida registration 65BNVL. I submitted a request to MCAC for wage and earnings information, insurance claims, and LPR data from May 23rd (when Stergiou rented the vehicle) to June 1st to attempt to identify locations Stergiou frequented. I also submitted an exigency request to T-Mobile to attempt to locate Stergious phone and identify a location where she is staying during the nights. T-Mobile provided six pings. The pings and times of these pings are listed below: 1256 hours -- 39.413313,-77.443292 -- 21 meters 1306 hours --39.413506,-77.443163-- 19 meters 1317 hours --39.413409,-77.443314-- 32 meters 1326 hours --39.413474,-77.443292-- 11 meters 1336 hours --39.413388,-77.443335-- 19 meters 1346 hours --39.413441,-77.443399-- 19 meters The above pings are mapped below. base64," style="height:290px; margin:5px 10px; width:350px" /> All of the pings provided by T-Mobile were in the area of the southeast corner of an apartment complex at 1704 Redfield Court, Frederick, MD 21702. Myself, CPL Mills, and SW McGuire responded to the apartment complex, which was a three-story building with apartments that had outdoor entrances. Due to the location of the pings, we decided to attempt to make contacts with the apartments in the south-east corner. I knocked on apartment 2B, which was answered by a white male who would refuse to identify himself to law enforcement. I introduced myself to the subject, showed him a picture of Olivia, and asked if he had seen her in the apartment complex recently. The subject appeared extremely nervous and hesitant to answer, but eventually told me that he had not. While speaking with him, however, Isaiah ran to the door. I called out for Stergiou, who eventually also came to the door. The male and Stergiou would not grant investigators access to the apartment in order to speak; however, they did consent to allowing SW McGuire into the residence. SW McGuire was able to assess Isaiahs well-being, health, and living conditions. It was determined that the best course of action would be for SW McGuire to build a rapport with Stergiou and the other subjects, and reintroduce investigators at a future date for further interviews. Case Status: This case remains open for further investigation.

Interview: Location: Dining Room, 33 Park Drive, Emmitsburg, MD. Interviewed: Kelly Free / Alexis Hollaway Interviewer: TFC Potvin 6852 Also Present: SW McGuire Narrative: On June 6th, 2023 at approximately 1315 hours, SW McGuire and I responded to the residence of Kelly Free (33 Park Drive, Emmitsburg, MD). Free currently has emergency custody of Alexis Hollaway, daughter of Olivia Stergiou. Once there, we interviewed both Free and Hollaway concurrently. This interview was recorded by an audio recorder. The following is a detailed synopsis of the interview and not an exact transcription. For further details, review the audio recording. Kelly started by providing some historical information of her sister, Stergiou. When Hollaway was approximately 2 years old, Stergiou dropped her off at Frees house and left her there for an extended period of time. Stergiou did this multiple times over the course of the next several years. In 2016 or 2017, Stergiou was arrested by the MSP for drug trafficking. Following this, Frees mother filed for and was granted custody of Hollaway. Several years later, Stergiou became pregnant with Isaiah Young and moved into her parents house at (8151 Rocky Ridge Road, Thurmont, MD 21788). During this time, according to Free, Stergiou was clean from any sort of narcotics and had gone to rehab. However, also during this time, Stergiou was stealing from local businesses in front of Young and Hollaway and also making Hollaway steal for her. On Friday, May 5th, Free picked up Young from day care because he was sick, brought him home to the Rocky Ridge address, and took care of the house and children while waiting for Stergiou to get home. Stergiou arrived at the residence at approximately 1715 hours, and Free left. Free, her husband, and Merle Moser (grandfather of Hollaway and Young) went to a restaurant in Pennsylvania. At approximately 1900 hours, Stergiou left the residence, leaving Young and Hollaway unattended in the residence. Moser returned to the residence at approximately 2200 hours, unaware that Isaiah was left there alone, and went to bed. On the morning of Saturday, May 6th, 2023, Free was doing yard work when she received several phone calls from Hollaway. Hollaway told Free that her mom left them alone. Free responded to the Rocky Ridge address and made multiple attempts to contact Stergiou by phone with no success. Free attempted to locate Stergiou at a known prior residence but was unable to make contact with her. Free stated that she contacted and filed a report with Child Protective Services (CPS) Saturday night when she still could not get a hold of Stergiou. Free contacted Darrell Young, father of Isaiah Young, explained what was happening, and asked for him to come get Isaiah. On Sunday, Darrell responded to the Rocky Ridge address and takes Isaiah. Stergiou returned home shortly after. Moser told Stergiou that she is no longer welcome to stay at his house. Stergiou took a small bag with her and left. Stergiou did not take Alexis with her. On Monday, May 8th, Free filed for and was granted emergency custody of Hollaway. Free stated that she has not heard from Stergiou since that weekend. I asked Hollaway to provide more detail about Stergiou stealing in front of her. Hollaway stated that she has steal Stergiou steal many times, items ranging from food and clothes to a toaster and a microwave. Hollaway could not recall a specific date, but stated that the most recent time was during the weekend of April 29th and 30th, when she stole a microwave from Walmart. Hollaway stated that she believes most of her clothes, including the clothes that she was currently wearing, were stolen. Hollaway stated that Stergiou is given food stamps. Instead of using them, she steals food to eat and sells the food stamps for cash. Hollaway stated that Stergiou would regularly leave her and Isaiah in the car alone while she went shopping, sometimes for as long as an hour. Hollaway stated that the most recent time this happened was approximately one month ago. Hollaway stated that she has seen Stergiou be physically abusive toward Isaiah. Hollaway stated Its mostly just ... the hitting. Or ... shell pick him up by one of his arms and just swing him. Hollaway could not remember a specific time that this occurred. Hollaway never observed physical injuries on Isaiah left by his mother. Hollaway recounted a story from the end of April when Isaiah was injured by a door at the Dollar General. However, it is unclear if this occurred because of the door closing into Isaiah or because of Isaiah being forced into the door.

Narrative: On Monday, June 5th, 2023, I authored a subpoena requesting information for residents living at 1074 Redfield Court, Frederick, MD 21703 in apartment 2B. This subpoena was electronically submitted to the Frederick County States Attorney Office. This subpoena was authorized and returned to me at 1401 hours. At approximately 1510 hours, SW McGuire and I responded to the Westwinds Apartments (1070 Greenwall Pl, Frederick, MD 21703) to serve the subpoena to the apartment manager. I was informed that the apartment is leased to Lee Fowler (04/12/1971). Fowler is the only occupant on the lease. A check of the MVA revealed that Fowler does not match the height, weight, or age of the unnamed male living at the apartment. While there, I observed the black Kia that is currently rented by Stergiou. SW McGuire and I knocked on the door in an attempt to contact Stergiou with negative results. On Tuesday, June 6th, 2023 at approximately 1330 hours, SW McGuire and I responded to 33 Park Drive, Emmitsburg, MD 21727 to speak with Kelly Free and Alexis Hollaway. See the related supplement for more detail of this interview. On Wednesday, June 7th, 2023at approximately 1110 hours, SW McGuire and I responded to the Redfield Court address in an attempt to contact Stergiou. The Kia was not observed in the parking lot and we made no attempts to contact Stergiou at the apartment. At 1735 hours, we responded back to the address and once again did not observe the vehicle in the parking lot. At approximately 1940 hours, I conducted a search of Stergious rental vehicle through Delta. I observed a traffic stop from May 14th at approximately 2320 hours. Stergiou was stopped for exceeding the speed limit traveling north on MD-194 in the area of Nicodemus Road by Trooper Devin (7046). I reviewed Trooper Devins body camera footage from the traffic stop and observed Isaiah in the back seat. I was unable to see if he was properly secured. On Thursday, June 8th, 2023 at approximately 1320 hours, SW McGuire and I once again responded to the Redfield Court address.This time, the Kia was observed in the parking lot. We attempted to make contact with Stergiou at the apartment with negative results. A closer inspection of the Kia revealed damage to the front drivers side from an apparent accident. A child car seat was observed in the rear drivers side passenger seat. The car seat had no padding or base, did not appear to be properly installed, and was slightly askew in the seat. During the course of this week, SW McGuire has made multiple additional attempts to communicate with Stergiou by phone in order to set up a time to meet. Stergiou has been minimal in her communication and has evaded setting up a meeting. Case Status: Case Open.

Narrative: On June 13th, 2023 at approximately 1600 hours, SW McGuire and I responded toThe Pediatric Center of Frederick (1475 Taney Ave # 201, Frederick, MD 21702) where Young was scheduled for an 18-month well visit due to Stergious continuous avoidance of contact with both MSP and CPS. Stergiou arrived at The Pediatric Center of Frederick at approximately 1650 hours, brought Young into the office, and was promptly brought by medical staff into an examination room. SW McGuire and I entered the facility and spoke with Youngs pediatrician to express our concerns. SW McGuire observed the well visit.18 month well-visit concluded that Isaiah has not gained any weight in the past 3 months, dropping from the 47th to 24th percentile. He will need to return in 1 month for a weight check and make adjustments to his diet. He was observed to have a fungal diaper rash and prescribed Nystatin. Due to concerns held by CPS, a safety plan was put into effect to remove Young from Stergious care and temporarily place him in the care of Free. I transported Young from the Pediatric Center of Frederick to the Frederick County Department of Social Services (FCDSS), where he was given to the care of Free. On June 14th, 2023 at approximately 1150 hours, I responded the FCDSS to conduct an interview with Stergiou that had been scheduled for 1200 hours. Stergiou arrived at approximately 1220 hours. Prior to the interview, SW McGuire and I determined that Stergiou would likely be more open and honest in speaking with SW McGuire than speaking with law enforcement. As such, the interview was primarily conducted by SW McGuire, with input as to questions and topics to discuss provided prior to the interview. See the associated supplement for details of the interview. At approximately 1430 hours, SW McGuire and I responded to the residence of Darrell Young (3223 St Augustine Ct, Olney MD 20832) to facilitate the transfer of custody of Isaiah from Free to Darrell.

Interview: Location: Interview room, Frederick County Department of Social Services (1888 N Market St, Frederick, MD 21701) Interviewed: Olivia Stergiou Interviewer: SW McGuire Also Present: TFC Potvin Narrative: On June 14th, 2023 at approximately 1150 hours, I responded the FCDSS to conduct an interview with Stergiou that had been scheduled for 1200 hours. Stergiou arrived at approximately 1220 hours. Prior to the interview, SW McGuire and I determined that Stergiou would likely be more open and honest in speaking with SW McGuire than speaking with law enforcement. As such, the interview was primarily conducted by SW McGuire, with input as to questions and topics to discuss provided prior to the interview. This interview was audibly recorded by a voice recorder. The following is a detailed synopsis of the interview and not a direct transcription. See the audio recording for more information. SW McGuire started by informing Stergiou that CPS had initially received a complaint regarding Stergiou leaving Isaiah and Alexis home alone overnight, as well as concerns regarding Isaiahs weight and nutrition. SW McGuire explained CPSs processes for investigations and findings. SW McGuire mentioned the condition of the car seat, which she and I observed on June 8th to have no padding or base and was not properly installed (forward facing, angled slightly, and not tightly secured by the seat belt). Stergiou stated that she found the padding and . . . it is washed and dried. Stergiou stated that it is in the car, but not put back on the car seat because it is difficult to put on. SW McGuire asked if the padding was on the day prior when she brought Isaiah to the pediatricians office. Stergiou initially stated yes but then recanted and stated that it was not. SW McGuire asked Stergiou to tell us about what had happened on May 5th, when she left Isaiah and Alexis home alone. Stergiou stated that she had gotten food from the food bank, and she was going to bring the food to the apartment. It was around 10 pm and Isaiah was sleeping. Alexis was still awake because shes a night owl. Stergiou, not wanting to wake Isaiah up, asked Alexis if she would care for Isaiah while Stergiou brought the food to the apartment. Stergiou stated that she was on Facebook and had reconnected with some old friends, eventually going over to their house to hang out. Stergiou stated that she was in contact with Alexis and that she knew Pappy would be home soon, he was out at the bar getting trashed. Stergiou is calls Merle Moser Pappy. Stergiou continued: One thing led to another, I kept putting it off saying Ill go home in an hour or two, Ill go home in an hour or two. And it, I didnt go home until Sunday around twelve, I guess? . . . I know its considered abandonment. But maybe in my mind, I guess I didnt feel like it was . . . My daughter, I felt like she is old enough but at the same time hes too young, whether she is old enough or not. . . and also Pappy wasnt there yet, he was at the bar. Stergiou stated that it was not her intention to be gone for that long, but that she fell into her old patterns. Stergiou expressed concerns of not having an outlet since the passing of her mother in October 2022. Stergiou stated that she stopped using when she found out that she was pregnant with Isaiah, and put herself into Orenda Center of Wellness in-patient rehabilitation care in August 2021. Following successful completion of that program, she moved into mom and Merles. Stergiou stayed clean while living there and kept herself away from those people, referring to friends that would encourage her to use narcotics. Stergiou expressed concerns of feeling like she needed to make up for lost time with Alexis, and appeared to show appropriately related emotions. Stergiou stated that she stayed clean by being focused on caring for her children and continuing mental health care. Stergiou stated that her drug of abuse is cocaine. She stated that she also smokes cigarettes. SW McGuire asked if that was what the slip was when you left for that weekend. Stergiou responded: It was heading there . . . It wasnt necessarily people that do that, it was just other people that I knew. I guess that they had different addictions, but it eventually did lead to that. Since that weekend, Stergiou has continued to abuse drugs and expressed that she feels that she needs help because she is disorganized. Stergiou expressed feeling overwhelmed by the thought of starting over. SW McGuire provided Stergiou with information about resources available to help her through the Frederick County Department of Social Services. Stergiou stated that the last time she used cocaine was approximately two days ago. Following the interview, SW McGuire and I went to the parking lot with Stergiou to observe Isaiahs car seat. The seat was still in the same condition.

Narrative: On July 11th, 2023 at 1317 hours, I responded to the Frederick County Court Commissioner and submitted an application for charges. A summons has been issued charging Stergiou for Neglect of a Minor and Confining an Unattended Child. Case Status: Case open pending service of summons.

Narrative: On August 1st, 2023, at approximately 1150 hours, I served Stergiou with the criminal summons for this case (D-111-CR-23-000083) charging her with Child Neglect (CR.3.602.1.(b))and Leaving Child Unattended (FL.5.801). Case Status: Case Closed

NARRATIVE: On Friday November 10, 2023 at approximately 1435 hours, I responded to the Maryland State Police Frederick barrack to serve Stergiou with the open criminal summons. Upon arrival, I made contact and served the criminal summons to Stergiou. Stergiou signed, and was provided a copy of, the criminal summons charging her with:1 1614 - CR, 3-602.1(b) : NEGLECT OF MINOR. All events occurred in Frederick County, Maryland. CASE STATUS: CLOSED, criminal summons served.
